Healthcare Fraud Detection

Marko Konte

6/26/2019

Paper Analysis: Predicting Healthcare Fraud in Medicaid: A Multidimensional Data Model and Analysis Techniques for Fraud Detection

The researches in the paper outlines a very broad, theoritcal overview of helathcare fraud and the factors which may cause it to happen. It was a good paper in laying out domain knowledge specific factors for readers to understand why healthcare fraud occurs. They explain the relationship between the main purpotrators of fraud (providers, patients, insurance carriers), the types of fraud (single large transactions or many little ones) and the 7 levelsof fraud within Sparrows model, from the lowest level being an individual fraudulent claim to level 7 being a cross- network conspiracy of fraud. An interesting point in the paper is that it highlightss that current fraud detection primarily focuses on levels 1-3. For its own model, the paper articulates its dimensionality and explains how a good analyst would take their time to look at a case starting from a low level (on sparrows chart) and moving up to wider group analysis. It will not be useful to apply level 7 analysis to a claim you are beggining to analyze due to there being too much noise in the info. If the analyst is able to detect connection between purpotrators in levels 1-3, they can move on to applying higher level analysis to determin if there is a larger network of fraud.

While the paper does a good job on a theoretical and high end explanation of healthcare fraud approach, there was not much detail in the actual analytical models that are used for the determination. THe paper strsses that it is a ‘roadmap’ for connecting to fraud, however they do not talk about what type of statistical approaches are most useful in detecting fraud from identified variables accross all 7 levels. The paper stresses that one problem in the industry is a lack of training data (marked fraudulent claims), therefore the study of healthcare fraud is a constant work in progress.

Conclusion:

As anticipated total payments was heavily influenced by the population of the given states. It was interesting that the standard the total payment per discharge by a procedure was also very heavy on the most populous states. This is either due to the expenses in those states being larger or that the discharge to procedure ratio is steady throughout the dataset.The standard deviation of total average payments will be useful in determining the procedures which have the greatest variance in how much was paid for them, which will be an important red flag for identifying healthcare fraud.

Next I looked at the payments data in relation to the above figures but with a scaling factor. I will continue to use the combined feature of state + the DRG figure and calculate the scaled figures for all the numeric variables Total Payments, Medicare Payments, Coverage, and Total Discharges.

scale_this <- function(x){
  (x - mean(x, na.rm=TRUE)) / sd(x, na.rm=TRUE)
} #Function to scale the data

Scaled <- payment %>% mutate(DRGState = paste(Provider.State, 
                                               DRG.Definition, sep="_"),                    
                                   ScTotPay = scale_this(Average.Total.Payments),
                                   ScTotCov = scale_this(Average.Covered.Charges),
                                   ScTotMed = scale_this(Average.Medicare.Payments),
                                   ScTotDis = scale_this(Total.Discharges))

Conclusion

The scaling factor of total payments will be a very useful feature when it is time to create our fraud detection models. There is a high correlation between total payments and medicare payments, this seemed strange because in reading the description Total Payments were covered by the patients plan and out of pocket costs, with medicare covering specifically the subsidized portion. While the scaling factor did normalize the data, the summarization of it still showed a heavy population effect.

Lead

Next we will look at differences in scaled values between the numeric variables of the dataset and compare them to the referral regions associated. While the state codes were previously identified with the DRG code, here we scale the differences in those numeric values and see what the specific referral city is where those major differences in values stem from.

#Total Scaled payments to referral refion
Scaled1 <- payment %>% mutate(DRGState = paste(Provider.State, 
                                              DRG.Definition, sep="_"),                    
                             ScCovMedDiff = scale_this(Average.Medicare.Payments - Average.Covered.Charges),
                             ScPayCovDiff = scale_this(Average.Total.Payments - Average.Covered.Charges),
                             ScPayMedDiff = scale_this(Average.Total.Payments - Average.Medicare.Payments),
                             ScPayperDis = scale_this(Average.Total.Payments/Total.Discharges))

Scaled1Sum <- Scaled1 %>% dplyr::group_by(DRGState, Hospital.Referral.Region.Description) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(Count = n(),
                   ScCovMedDiff = sum(ScCovMedDiff),
                   ScPayCovDiff = sum(ScPayCovDiff),
                   ScPayMedDiff = sum(ScPayMedDiff),
                   ScPayperDis = sum(ScPayperDis))

Conclusion:

In looking at the most amount of medicare statement without considering state, there was a concentration of procedures that is generally for an older population, like heart failure. When considering the per state amounts paid, while there was a skew to the populous regionds still, there was different relationships between the amount spent on medicare and coverage/ total amounts between different states.

##Final Conclusion:

  • Total Payments: – We were able to analyze total payments made for coverage on an absolute manner and scaled. The most indicative value from an absolute value perspective was standard deviation, which showed the states/ procedures that were above the norm. – While standard deviation of total payments had a factor of population which played an impact. It identified several
  • Scaled features: – Normalize all of the numeric variables in order to identify relative value of payments, coverage, and medicare payments. – Identify regionally scaled values which had outliers when calculated for the difference between total payment, coverage, and medicare payments.
  • Medicare payments: – First taking a holistic, non state look at medicare payments, we were able to identify the procedures which recieved most medicare payments regardless of state. – Next we looked at procedures per state that medicare funds were being paid to. We identified that while total medicare payments tended to highly concentrate in California, when looking at the difference between total payment and medicare, the results were highly concentrated in Texas.

We had identified several procedures within the states of California, Georgia, Illinois, Alabama, and Maine which had very diverse amount of payments or coverages paid. This will be good to keep in mind as a preliminary ‘red flag’ before applying a predictive model for fraud.
